  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. It is a serious criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear lawful.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (codified at 18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). The penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Substantial fines**: Individuals can face fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n- **Prison sentences**: Convictions can result in up to **20 years in federal prison** for each offense.\n- **Additional penalties**: Assets involved in the laundering scheme may be forfeited to the government.\n\nState laws may also criminalize money laundering, with penalties varying depending on the jurisdiction and the amount of money involved. In many cases, money laundering is associated with other crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or terrorism, which can lead to even harsher penalties.\n\nIf you are facing allegations of money laundering or have questions about the legal implications, it is crucial to consult with an experienced criminal defense attorney.",
